<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="518" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,881,1377]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,881,908]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Chrysogorgiids with uniplanar flabellate or lyrate colonies, with long terminal branches. Axis with or without calcareous deposits, becoming very thin and flexible at terminal branches. Polyps biserial on all sides of terminal and subterminal branches, widely spaced or more crowded terminally. Sclerites present or absent; if present, in the form of very thin scales (double disks or double pads), with finely serrated edges (
<bibRefCitation author="Bayer, F. M. &amp; Muzik, K. M." box="[1143,1427,990,1016]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" pagination="65 - 90" refId="ref5949" refString="Bayer, F. M. &amp; Muzik, K. M. (1976) New genera and species of the holaxonian family Chrysogorgiidae (Octocorallia: Gorgonacea). Zoologische Mededelingen, 50 (5), 65 - 90." type="journal article" year="1976">Bayer &amp; Muzik 1976: 79</bibRefCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="518" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,881,1377]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1026,1052]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">Remarks.</emphasis>
Six species currently belong to this genus (
<tableCitation box="[794,877,1026,1052]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="7.[151,239,590,616]" captionTargetBox="[165,2011,627,1099]" captionText="TABLE 1. Valid species of the genus Trichogorgia Hickson, 1904, their morphological characters and distribution.?unknown; -absent or rare." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/FAC257C95B2CFFE082E0FD84F9228227" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" tableUuid="FAC257C95B2CFFE082E0FD84F9228227">Table 1</tableCitation>
), which fit into at least four general colony forms: lyrate, flabellate, slender planar and bushy (
<figureCitation box="[658,750,1062,1088]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1922,1947]" captionTargetBox="[158,1433,205,1803]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,196,1815]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Forms and distribution of the genus Trichogorgia. A: four common colony shapes in the genus (left to right): lyrate, flabellate, slender planar and bushy, respectively; B: comparison between bathymetric ranges of Trichogorgia species; C: distribution map for the genus. Depth given in meters (m)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3616837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3616837/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). A seventh dubious species was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hiles, I. L." box="[1293,1436,1062,1088]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" pagination="195 - 206" refId="ref6585" refString="Hiles, I. L. (1899) The Gorgonacea collected by Dr. Willey. Zoological Results based on material from New Britain, New Guinea, Loyalty Islands and elsewhere, collected during the years 1895 1896 and 1897, by Arthur Willey, Part 2, 195 - 206" type="book chapter" year="1899">Hiles (1899)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hiles" authorityYear="1899" box="[183,459,1098,1124]" class="Anthozoa" family="Chrysogorgiidae" genus="Chrysogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="constricta">
<emphasis box="[183,459,1098,1124]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">Chrysogorgia constricta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from New Britain, which was later transferred to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hickson" authorityYear="1904" box="[1036,1183,1098,1124]" class="Anthozoa" family="Chrysogorgiidae" genus="Trichogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1036,1183,1098,1124]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">Trichogorgia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kukenthal, W." box="[1229,1432,1098,1124]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" pagination="1 - 946" refId="ref6638" refString="Kukenthal, W. (1919) Gorgonaria. Wissenschftliche Ergenbisse der Deutschen Tiefsee-Expedition auf dem Dampfer &quot; Valdivia &quot;, 13 (2), 1 - 946." type="journal article" year="1919">Kükenthal (1919)</bibRefCitation>
. Soon after its description, authors started to question its identity (
<bibRefCitation author="Versluys, J." box="[881,1045,1134,1160]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" pagination="1 - 120" refId="ref6993" refString="Versluys, J. (1902) Die Gorgoniden der Siboga-Expedition. I. Die Chrysogorgiiden. Siboga Expeditie, 13, 1 - 120." type="journal article" year="1902">Versluys 1902</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kukenthal, W." box="[1057,1240,1134,1160]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" pagination="1 - 946" refId="ref6638" refString="Kukenthal, W. (1919) Gorgonaria. Wissenschftliche Ergenbisse der Deutschen Tiefsee-Expedition auf dem Dampfer &quot; Valdivia &quot;, 13 (2), 1 - 946." type="journal article" year="1919">Kükenthal 1919</bibRefCitation>
). The uncertainty emerged mostly because its body wall sclerites are spindles arranged in eight-line chevrons (
<bibRefCitation author="Hiles, I. L." box="[1170,1295,1170,1196]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" pagination="195 - 206" refId="ref6585" refString="Hiles, I. L. (1899) The Gorgonacea collected by Dr. Willey. Zoological Results based on material from New Britain, New Guinea, Loyalty Islands and elsewhere, collected during the years 1895 1896 and 1897, by Arthur Willey, Part 2, 195 - 206" type="book chapter" year="1899">Hiles 1899</bibRefCitation>
, p. 195–196, pl. XXII. figs. 8, 9, 10), whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hickson" authorityYear="1904" box="[552,699,1206,1232]" class="Anthozoa" family="Chrysogorgiidae" genus="Trichogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[552,699,1206,1232]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">Trichogorgia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, sclerites are only scales, when present (
<bibRefCitation author="Williams, G. C." box="[1155,1326,1206,1232]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" pagination="181 - 296" refId="ref7060" refString="Williams, G. C. (1992) The Alcyonacea of southern Africa. Gorgonian octocorals (Coelenterata, Anthozoa). Annals of the South African Museum, 101 (8), 181 - 296." type="journal article" year="1992">Williams 1992</bibRefCitation>
), never in chevron. It is also uncertain if specimens from Amboina Island (
<bibRefCitation author="Hentschel, E." box="[882,1061,1242,1268]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" pagination="643 - 652" refId="ref6497" refString="Hentschel, E. (1903) Gorgonacea von Amboina und Thursday Island. Zoologische Forschungsreisen in Australien und dem Malayischen Archipel. Ausgefuhrt in den Jahren 1891 - 1893 von Richard Semon, 5. Band, 6. Lieferung. Denkschriften der Medicinisch-Naturwissenschaftlichen Gesellschaft zu Jena, 8, 643 - 652." type="journal article" year="1903">Hentschel 1903</bibRefCitation>
) correspond to the same species. Herein, I suggest to keep that species in its original genus (
<taxonomicName box="[806,961,1278,1304]" class="Anthozoa" family="Chrysogorgiidae" genus="Chrysogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[806,961,1278,1304]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">Chrysogorgia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), until the 
<typeStatus box="[1082,1141,1279,1305]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">types</typeStatus>
are re-examined. With the two new names given in this manuscript, the genus expands its diversity to eight species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1322,1349,1377]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,881,1377]" box="[199,1322,1349,1377]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1349,1376]" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">Distribution.</emphasis>
Probably cosmopolitan, mostly found at mesophotic depths, 
<quantity box="[1038,1173,1350,1377]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.37" metricValueMax="6.62" metricValueMin="0.12" pageId="1" pageNumber="518" unit="m" value="337.0" valueMax="662.0" valueMin="12.0">12 to 662 m</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[1188,1309,1350,1376]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1922,1947]" captionTargetBox="[158,1433,205,1803]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,196,1815]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Forms and distribution of the genus Trichogorgia. A: four common colony shapes in the genus (left to right): lyrate, flabellate, slender planar and bushy, respectively; B: comparison between bathymetric ranges of Trichogorgia species; C: distribution map for the genus. Depth given in meters (m)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3616837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3616837/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="518">Fig. 1B, C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
